<body>

<h1>How I Built My Mini Search Engine</h1>

<div class="section">

<h2>1. The Idea</h2>

<p>

I wanted to understand how websites respond when users type something.

Search engines like Google take input and decide what to open.

So I built a simple version.

</p>

</div>



<div class="section">

<h2>2. The Problem</h2>

<p>

Users type different words.

The website must read the word and decide what to do.

Example:

youtube → open YouTube.

github → open GitHub.

</p>

</div>



<div class="section">

<h2>3. How Input Is Read</h2>

<code>

let text =
document.getElementById("search").value;

</code>

<p>

document = entire webpage.

getElementById("search") finds the search box.

.value reads what the user typed.

</p>

</div>



<div class="section">

<h2>4. Decision Making Logic</h2>

<code>

if(text === "youtube"){

window.location =
"https://youtube.com";

}

</code>

<p>

The IF statement checks the word.

If it matches youtube,

the browser moves to that website.

window.location changes pages.

</p>

</div>



<div class="section">

<h2>5. Why JavaScript Was Needed</h2>

<p>

HTML builds structure.

But HTML cannot make decisions.

JavaScript adds behaviour and logic.

It allows interaction.

</p>

</div>



<div class="section">

<h2>6. What Happens When User Clicks Search</h2>

<code>

<button onclick="searchSite()">

</code>

<p>

When button is clicked,

JavaScript function runs.

It reads input and decides destination.

</p>

</div>



<div class="section">

<h2>7. What I Learned</h2>

<ul>

<li>HTML creates pages.</li>

<li>JavaScript controls behaviour.</li>

<li>Websites connect using links.</li>

<li>Decision logic controls navigation.</li>

</ul>

</div>



<div class="section">

<h2>8. Future Improvements</h2>

<ul>

<li>Add more websites.</li>

<li>Allow partial search matching.</li>

<li>Add styling and animations.</li>

</ul>

</div>



